04886nmm a2200709Ia 9781501730481DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1083621271  a97815017304817 a10.7591/97815017304812doi  a(DE-B1597)503535  a(OCoLC)1035778836  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPG3020.5.P436b.R457 201804a891.709/3572231 aReischl, Katherine M. H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhotographic Literacy :bCameras in the Hands of Russian Authors /cKatherine M. H. Reischl. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b20 color photos, 78 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPhotography, introduced to Russia in 1839, was nothing short of a sensation. Its rapid proliferation challenged the other arts, including painting and literature, as well as the very integrity of the self. If Leo Tolstoy and Fyodor Dostoevsky greeted the camera with skepticism in the nineteenth century, numerous twentieth-century authors welcomed it with a warm embrace. As Katherine M. H. Reischl shows in Photographic Literacy, authors as varied as Leonid Andreev, Ilya Ehrenburg, and Alexander Solzhenitsyn picked up the camera and reshaped not only their writing practices but also the sphere of literacy itself.For these authors, a single photograph or a photograph as illustration is never an endpoint; their authorial practices continually transform and animate the frozen moment. But just as authors used images to shape the reception of their work and selves, Russian photographers—including Sergei Prokudin-Gorsky and Alexander Rodchenko—used text to shape the reception of their visual work. From the diary to print, the literary word imbues that photographic moment with a personal life story, and frames and reframes it in the writing of history. In this primer on photographic literacy, Reischl argues for the central place that photography has played in the formation of the Russian literary imagination over the course of roughly seventy years. From image to text and back again, she traces the visual consciousness of modern Russian literature as captured through the lens of the Russian author-photographer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterature and photographyzRussiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiterature and photographyzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aPhotography in literature. 0aRussian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhotography. 4aSoviet & East European History.  aphotography, literature, Russia, USSR, Soviet Union, Leonid Andreev, Ilya Ehrenburg, Alexander Solzhenitsyn, Sergie Prokudin-Gorsky, Alexander Rodchenko, visual consciousness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishz978311060418408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2018z9783110603187oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173048140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501730481423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501730481/original  a978-3-11-060418-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell Uni